:: 42_story-text-eng [nobr]
<p class="bold">These are Transform tiles from the 1970s – based on a design by German sculptor, Fritz Steller. He made incredible art for civic buildings across the UK.</p>
<p>Every tile looks slightly different. When they were fired in their kilns, each responded differently to the flames, revealing distinct patterns and colours. Theatre experts also helped with their fitting – they knew the effect the tiles would have on the theatre’s sound.</p>

<div class="quote">
<p>"It's a fascinating space…it enables you to do what you want with it, sonically, from a sound point of view."</p>
</div>

<p>Hey, that’s Tayo Akinbode! Panto musical director. A genius. And who’s this?</p>

<div class="quote">
<p>"It always felt very intimate. Always felt like...if you wanted to, and if you, you know, were confident enough of what you were doing, you had the audience that right there...and acoustically, too. Vocally was always kind of easy to play, really, compared with so many places I played."</p>
</div>

<p>That’s Steffan Rhodri, you might recognise him from Gavin & Stacey. He's performed on this stage countless times and I agree, the stage and sound connects you to the audiences - it’s special. </p>

<div class="quote">
<p>"I think as a child, I saw them as, like, like, a big bar of chocolate. I love that theatre because there are no bad seats. It's like a big hug. Everybody's in there together."</p>
</div>

<p>Catrin Aaron has gazed up at people in 35 productions here.  Her mum, a nurse, used to bring her here when she was little, from nearby Rhyl. She went on to work at the Royal Shakespeare Company.</p>
<p>Being part of Theatr Clwyd is like being part of a family. Let’s jump around the theatre to find people who can tell you more...</p>

